Received following from the Economist Data Journalist. Slightly different perspective than I’d seen previously but ties a couple points together. FYI only “The Democratic Party is yet to hold its first presidential primary, but many would-be nominees have already surged, sagged or dropped out altogether. Joe Biden has been the front-runner ever since pollsters started asking primary voters about their intentions. But just behind him, there has been plenty of movement. Elizabeth Warren had a surge in the autumn, nearly but not quite catching Mr Biden; she has since fallen back. Next to enjoy a bounce was Pete Buttigieg, who benefited from Ms Warren’s declining popularity among college-educated whites. His numbers have now slid a bit and Bernie Sanders is doing better. What explains these ups and downs? Almost all of the variation in support for the different Democratic candidates so far can be traced to movement among white voters, particularly college-educated ones. According to YouGov’s survey for The Economist of Democrats who say they intend to vote in the primaries, the group has oscillated wildly between support for Ms Warren, Mr Sanders and Mr Buttigieg. This has been the main group supplying Mr Biden’s chief competitors—Mr Sanders and Ms Warren—with enough votes to be contenders. Ms Warren pulled in support from over 20% of college-educated whites at the start of the campaign, and currently wins nearly 30% of them. Mr Sanders has recently become the leading choice of whites without a degree. Non-white Democratic voters, by contrast, have been much more stalwart in their support for Mr Biden, especially those without college degrees. They have grown only more inclined to the former vice-president as the more progressive candidates have swapped places behind him. This is, on the face of it, odd. During President Donald Trump’s administration, white, liberal Democrats have become much more sensitive to racial injustice than they were when Barack Obama was president. You can see this in their increased awareness of racial discrimination as a barrier to economic and social progress. Yet when it comes to casting a vote in the primaries, they have avoided non-white candidates. They also favour more radical policies than do African-Americans. It used to be labour unions that acted as a counterweight to left-wing social movements within the Democratic coalition. Now it seems that African-Americans are playing that role. Without them, Ms Warren or Mr Sanders, not Mr Biden, would probably be the favourite.“

Sanders appears to be leading, but the most recent poll (Suffolk) is somewhat misleading. While it shows Sanders with a wide margin, the poll combines both individuals who both currently support a candidate or are "leaning" toward a candidate. The leaning voters could easily change their mind. Prior recent polling (without leaning factored in) shows a much closer race, with a large segment still undecided. Results in Iowa, where recent polls are few and appear to indicate a tighter race, could influence NH voters to a certain extent. Nevertheless, Sanders won by a large margin in 2016 and he is well-known in New Hampshire. The difference, however, was there were really only 2 viable candidates in 2016--Sanders and Clinton. Sanders consistently led in polling averages in the month leading up to the primary by 8-10 points, with increasing support as the election neared. He ultimately won 60/38%. Here, on the other hand, 4 candidates make the assessment more complicated, as Biden and Sanders carry less than 50% support (about 40-45%) between the two of them, with Warren and Buttigieg garnering close to 30%. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/nh/new_hampshire_democratic_presidential_primary-6276.html Since the NH primary is only a week after the Iowa caucus, it seems unlikely that any of the four will drop out unless they do incredibly poorly. We can thus expect a fairly divided support. Buttigieg has surged recently, and some of the other policy questions reveal an independent streak in voters that he could appeal to.

Sanders leads in current polling, per 538, though only marginally. He also leads in fundraising, per 4th quarter 2019 FEC filings; the lead fundraiser has been the New Hampshire winner more than half the time, so giving Sanders a 15% bump over initial base rate estimate of a four way race. Biden is a close second in 538's aggregated polls, with ~20% support, and is the only candidate to break 30% support since April 2019, so adding 5%. Biden is third in fundraising behind Mayor Pete who, along with Elizabeth Warren, are currently both polling around at close to 15%.

Already adjusting from my first forecast after reading some of the other predictions and reconsidering my base rate strategy, which I think may have anchored me high considering the factors that are unique to 2020 (namely the number of candidates fundraising amounts in the same relative ballpark). So my change here is to increase the amount I am letting the polls and five thirty eight's forecast influence me, bumping Biden up and bringing Bernie down. However, I did not want to drop Bernie below 50% minimum because I still agree with my overall assessment. Will watch and update.

I started by finding a base rate for the past five democratic primaries in New Hampshire (2000-2016): how often the lead fundraiser as of the end of the fourth quarter of the preceding year won the New Hampshire primary. This happened 3 out of 5 times (Obama 2012, Clinton 2008, Gore 2000), or 60%. So because Bernie Sanders is the lead fundraiser, I start with him at a 60% chance of winning the most delegates. While I'm going with this for now, to see where it leads, I do have some reservations: primarily that in most of the past NH primaries I cited, there were not SO many candidates with solid fundraising numbers. So I might reneg on this approach later.
